Highway Impact Simulation¶

We will analyze the effect of the completion of the Santa Monica Bridge that is currently under construction. This bridge is intended to address traffic congestion by connecting the Ortigas CBD with Bonifacio Global City (BGC).

def shortest_distance(graph, o_c, dest_c):
    """
    Creates a GeoDataFrame containing the edges of the shortest path
    from an origin to a destination point. These edges are represented 
    as linestrings that can be plotted on a map (folium works)
    
    Also prints the distance of the computed path.
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    graph : Graph 
        osmnx graph of the area containing the points
        
    o_c : tuple of floats
        coordinates of origin point in Long/Lat format
        
    dest_c : tuple of floats
        coordinates of destination point in Long/Lat format
        
    Returns
    -------
    path_gdf : GeoDataFrame
    
    shortest_dist : float
    """
    gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame([{"geometry": Point(o_c)},
                            {"geometry": Point(dest_c)}], 
                           crs={'init':'epsg:4326'})
    gdf.to_crs({'init': 'epsg:32651'}, inplace=True)
    origin_point = gdf.loc[0].geometry
    dest_point = gdf.loc[1].geometry
    
    O = osx.get_nearest_node(graph, (origin_point.y, origin_point.x), 
                             method='euclidean', return_dist=True)
    D = osx.get_nearest_node(graph, (dest_point.y, dest_point.x), 
                             method='euclidean', return_dist=True)
#     display(gdf)
    path = nx.shortest_path(graph, source=O[0], target=D[0])
    path_edges = []
    adj = graph.adj
    for i in range(0,len(path)-1):
        edges = adj[path[i]][path[i+1]]
        min_length = float("inf")
        min_edge = None
        for key in edges: 
            edge = edges[key]
            if edge["length"] < min_length:
                min_length = edge["length"]
                min_edge = edge
        path_edges.append((path[i],path[i+1],min_edge))
    node_dict = dict(graph.nodes)
    
    gdf_builder = [] 
    for edge in path_edges:
        u = node_dict[edge[0]]
        v = node_dict[edge[1]]
        curr = edge[2] 
        if "geometry" not in curr: 
            geom = LineString([(u['x'],u['y']),(v['x'],v['y'])])
        else:
            geom = curr['geometry']
        res = {"source": edge[0], "target": edge[1], 
           "distance": edge[2]['length'],"geometry":geom}
        gdf_builder.append(res)
    path_gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(gdf_builder,crs={'init':'epsg:32651'})
    path_gdf.to_crs({'init':'epsg:4326'},inplace=True)
    path_gdf
    
    shortest_dist = path_gdf['distance'].sum()
#     print('distance:', shortest_dist)
    
    # compute shortest path
#     best_path = nx.shortest_path_length(graph, Point(o_c), Point(dest_c))   
    return path_gdf, shortest_dist

def map_builder(graph, loc, dest, F_list, n):
    """
    NOTE: keep all inputs in lat/long format. 
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    loc : tuple
        center from where to make the map
        
    dest : tuple
        destination of all pts
        
    F_list : list of tuples
        all origin points
    """
    curr_map = folium.Map(location = loc, zoom_start=n)
    
    folium.Marker(
            location=dest,
            popup='Destination',
            icon=folium.Icon(color='red')
            ).add_to(curr_map)
    
#     gdfs = []
    dists = []
    
    for pair in F_list:
        try:
            gdf, dist = shortest_distance(graph, pair[::-1], dest[::-1])
            dists.append(dist)

            geo_json = gdf.to_json()
            path = folium.features.GeoJson(geo_json)
            path.add_to(curr_map)

            folium.Marker(
                location=pair).add_to(curr_map)
#             print('added to map')
        except:
            print('location outside graph')

    return curr_map
In [5]:
def compute_time(speed, distance, return_minutes=True):
    """
    Parameters
    ----------
    speed : int
        speed in km/h
    distance : float
        distance in m
    """
    ms_speed = speed/3.6
    seconds = distance/ms_speed
    mins = seconds/60
    hours = mins/60
    if return_minutes:
        return round(mins, 2)
    else:
        return round(hours, 2)

Load and Plot Graph¶

You can specify what types of streets to extract by passing a string to network_type. These options include the following:

  • drive – get drivable public streets (but not service roads)
  • drive_service – get drivable public streets, including service roads
  • walk – get all streets and paths that pedestrians can use (this network type ignores one-way directionality)
  • bike – get all streets and paths that cyclists can use
  • all – download all (non-private) OSM streets and paths
  • all_private – download all OSM streets and paths, including private-access ones
In [6]:

Identify Nodes Santa Monica Bridge Connects¶

If we want to simulate the creation of a new bridge or road, we need to make computations on a separate graph object. We load graph_after as the road network we'll be creating the bridge in.

In [11]:
p1 = 14.566374, 121.054880
p2 = 14.564870, 121.054464

center = 14.565958, 121.054762

graph_after = osx.graph_from_point(center, distance=1500, 
                             network_type='drive_service',
                             retain_all=True)

# graph = osx.project_graph(graph, to_crs={'init': 'epsg:32651'})

Checking the nodes and edges of a graph is standard practice, although I do this just to inspect the features of the edges table. This will give us an idea on what the features our new edge (or bridge in this case) will have when we generate it.

In [12]:
nodes, edges = osx.graph_to_gdfs(graph_after, nodes=True, edges=True)

Here, we need to get the nodes closest to the starting and end points of Santa Monica bridge. O and D will serve as starting points. add_edge does exactly what its name says. We set a key value to it just so we can check later on if the edge was indeed created with the intended features.

Comparing Centrality¶

In [25]:
# creates a dictionary of nodes and their associated centralities
node_centrality_a = nx.closeness_centrality(graph_before)
In [26]:
# turn it into a dataframe
df = pd.DataFrame(data=pd.Series(node_centrality_a).sort_values(), columns=['cc'])

df['colors'] = osx.get_colors(n=len(df), cmap='inferno', start=0.2)
df = df.reindex(graph_before.nodes())
nc = df['colors'].tolist()
fig, ax = osx.plot_graph(graph_before, bgcolor='k', node_size=30, node_color=nc, node_edgecolor='none', node_zorder=2,
                        edge_color='#555555', edge_linewidth=1.5, edge_alpha=1, fig_height=10)
In [27]:
# edge closeness centrality: convert graph to a line graph so edges become nodes and vice versa
edge_centrality_a = nx.closeness_centrality(nx.line_graph(graph_before))
In [28]:
# list of edge values for the orginal graph
ev = [edge_centrality_a[edge + (0,)] for edge in graph_before.edges()]

# color scale converted to list of colors for graph edges
norm = colors.Normalize(vmin=min(ev)*0.8, vmax=max(ev))
cmap = cm.ScalarMappable(norm=norm, cmap=cm.inferno)
ec = [cmap.to_rgba(cl) for cl in ev]

# color the edges in the original graph with closeness centralities in the line graph
fig, (ax1) = osx.plot_graph(graph_before, bgcolor='k', axis_off=True, node_size=0, node_color='w', 
                         node_edgecolor='gray', node_zorder=2,
                        edge_color=ec, edge_linewidth=1.5, edge_alpha=1, fig_height=10)
